<font color="#FF0000">DIDDY-BOPPING?</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jul  9 22:05:56 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
As to the two individuals who shot themselves, seems like they were suicides or suicidal attempts, not attempts to get out of doing their jobs. As you know, some folks, men and women, are predisposed to such when faced with the stress in combat situation or situations for which they have no control. I am reminded of one reported suicide of a soilder in Haiti, for whatever reason, off'ed himself, and the stresses were not even comparable. You may be right about cases of self inflicted injuries reported as other as I know of one KIA from my platoon who was listed as &quot;killed by mis-adventure&quot;, i.e., accident, when in reality, he intercepted a B-40 rocket in his mid-section.<br><br>
As I absolutely refuse to get involved in the debate in political/philosophical stances between yourself, Tom Dier, Doc Spatz or any others, I do want to make one other thing clear. I was with the First Cav Division from Nov. '67 to Feb. '70, and at no time do I ever remember &quot;diddy-bopping&quot; in the bush. I was wrong in my assumption that you and I were probably in the same ops together, because as I pointed out to another, my unit was never involved with civilian populations, we were never in anything other than free-fire zones, etc. I will back up your statement to this point regarding civilians, though. I have witnessed the NVA units using civilians to walk ahead of the military unit, using them as &quot;minesweepers&quot; and to detonate any AA's. Other than that, I cannot give any accounts of civilians atrocities or make any case to back your point. My unit also was never involved with any mechanized operations either. <br><br>
When I am communicating with a member of the marine corps, I give him the utmost respect that one member of the armed services can give another. When we are close, I will joke with him about the number of times that we had to pull QRF's to pull some jarhead unit outta shit. I will, also joke with that individual that the respect that I have for any member of the Corps stems from these troops wanting to take on the entire NVA with only a handfull of men and hand-me-down weapons and equipment. But, behind these jokes, I will never denegrate the Marine Corps or any member of such. I have that much respect for those that served in the Corps. The truth be known, we had pulled units of the 101st out of tough times and we needed assist more than once ourselves. <br><br>
I want you to know, Cook that I extend that same respect to you and your compatriots. From the time that I came incountry in I Corps to when we were moved to III Corps about a year later, my platoon had suffered many casualties. We were not diddy-bopping in the woods. We worked mostly in platoon size operations and, only on occasion, did we link up for company size operations. We never went to spend any time at rear base area waiting for our next operation, as, from my perspective, it was just one long fucken operation in the bush.<br><br>
So when you characterize the First Cav as such, I am in fact sensitive that this denegration of my platoon's role and sacrifices extend to those for which I had to medivac out. Please give other units of other armed services the same respect that I extend to you and and the Marine Corps. I believe that I, the men in my unit, and those medivaced out, deserve such. You did your job with heart and soul and blood. I did my job with heart and soul and blood.<br><br>
I thank you for clearing up the issue of &quot;self inflicted injuries.
<p><code>-- docdel@maui.net  (Doc Del) </code><p>


